data.content:
Here are the idiomatic MSTest replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0, "Expected at least one user");
    // or: CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty() isn't built-in,
    // so Assert.IsTrue is fine here, but add a message.

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "All users should be active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null);
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` or keep `IsTrue` with a message | Better failure output |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows "expected 3, got 5" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and message |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` — item exists
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order & elements
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` — no duplicates

The biggest win is `Assert.AreEqual` over `Assert.IsTrue` for comparisons — on failure it tells you *what* the actual value was.
